# Rendering Multiple Items Using Arrays and Objects (`map()`)

## Simple Definition

> **The `map()` method is used in React to traverse an array and create JSX elements for each item.**

In simple words:

> **`map()` takes each item in an array and returns a React element for it.**

---

# Why Use `map()`?

Suppose you have three fruits.

Without `map()`:

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <>
            <h2>Apple</h2>
            <h2>Mango</h2>
            <h2>Orange</h2>
        </>
    );
}
```

This works, but imagine having **100 fruits**.

Instead, use an array.

---

# Rendering an Array

```jsx
function App() {

    const fruits = ["Apple", "Mango", "Orange"];

    return (
        <>
            {
                fruits.map((fruit) => (
                    <h2>{fruit}</h2>
                ))
            }
        </>
    );
}
```

Output

```
Apple
Mango
Orange
```

---

# Understanding `map()`

```javascript
fruits.map((fruit) => (
    <h2>{fruit}</h2>
))
```

| Part | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `fruits` | Array |
| `.map()` | Loops through every element |
| `fruit` | Current element |
| `<h2>{fruit}</h2>` | JSX returned for each element |

---

# Using Index

```jsx
const fruits = ["Apple", "Mango", "Orange"];

function App() {

    return (
        <>
            {
                fruits.map((fruit, index) => (
                    <h2>{index} - {fruit}</h2>
                ))
            }
        </>
    );

}
```

Output

```
0 - Apple
1 - Mango
2 - Orange
```

