# Traversing an Array of Objects

```jsx
const students = [

    { id: 1, name: "Rahul", age: 22 },

    { id: 2, name: "John", age: 20 },

    { id: 3, name: "Alice", age: 21 }

];

function App() {

    return (

        <>
            {
                students.map((student) => (

                    <div>

                        <h2>{student.name}</h2>

                        <p>{student.age}</p>

                    </div>

                ))
            }

        </>

    );

}
```

Output

```
Rahul
22

John
20

Alice
21
```

---

# Using `key` (Very Important)

Every element created by `map()` should have a unique **key**.

```jsx
students.map((student) => (

    <div key={student.id}>

        <h2>{student.name}</h2>

        <p>{student.age}</p>

    </div>

))
```

Why?

- Helps React identify each item.
- Improves performance.
- Prevents rendering issues.

